{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514647","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514647"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:24:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12344"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12344"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.02,0.65,0.02,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4864"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53829"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4864"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12344"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39289"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1106"},{"type":"tags","id":"4975"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"11959"},{"type":"tags","id":"12804"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7854"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7924"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16096"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42741"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43320"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53829","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53829"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic after a recent positive pregnancy test. She has a medical history of epilepsy diagnosed six months ago, currently treated with sodium valproate. She initially presented with multiple episodes of loss of consciousness with stiffening of the body followed by uncontrollable jerking. Each episode usually lasted from seconds to two minutes, followed by confusion and exhaustion. Her medication is keeping her symptoms well controlled. She does not take any other regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate statement regarding the management of her epilepsy during pregnancy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue sodium valproate as the benefits outweigh the risks","Sodium valproate has a similar risk of birth defects compared to other anti-epileptics","Sodium valproate should be avoided due to increased risk of birth defects","Sodium valproate is safe to use during the first trimester only","Sodium valproate can be used safely if folic acid supplementation is given"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario, the most appropriate statement is that \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium valproate should be avoided due to increased risk of birth defects\u003C/strong\u003E. Valproate is a known teratogen associated with increased rates of fetal structural abnormalities, neural tube defects, and fetal growth restriction. The risk of major congenital malformations is dose-dependent and can be as high as 10% with high doses of valproate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinuing sodium valproate as the benefits outweigh the risks\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate. While seizure control is important during pregnancy, the significant teratogenic effects of valproate make it unsuitable for use during pregnancy when safer alternatives are available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe statement that \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium valproate has a similar risk of birth defects compared to other anti-epileptics\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. Valproate carries a higher risk of major congenital malformations compared to other anti-epileptic drugs such as lamotrigine or levetiracetam.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESuggesting that \u003Cstrong\u003Esodium valproate is safe to use during the first trimester only\u003C/strong\u003E is misleading. The first trimester is actually the most critical period for organogenesis, and exposure to valproate during this time carries the highest risk of major malformations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESodium valproate can be used safely if folic acid supplementation is given\u003C/strong\u003E is not correct. While folic acid supplementation is important for all pregnant women, especially those on anti-epileptic medications, it does not negate the teratogenic effects of valproate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management would be to switch from sodium valproate to a safer alternative, such as lamotrigine, which is generally considered to have the lowest risk of teratogenicity among anti-epileptic drugs. This transition should be done under close medical supervision, ideally before conception. Additionally, all women of childbearing potential taking anti-epileptic drugs should receive folic acid supplementation (5 mg daily) to reduce the risk of neural tube defects. Management of epilepsy during pregnancy requires careful consideration of the risks and benefits of treatment, with close collaboration between neurology and obstetrics for optimal care.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Sodium valproate is a known teratogen and should be avoided during pregnancy due to increased risk of birth defects.","Folic acid supplementation (5 mg daily) should be given to pregnant women taking anti-epileptic medications.","Management of epilepsy during pregnancy requires careful consideration of risks and benefits, with lamotrigine generally considered the safest option."],"references":["Dupont S, Vercueil L. Epilepsy and pregnancy: What should the neurologists do? Rev Neurol (Paris). 2021 Mar;177(3):168-179. doi: 10.1016/j.neurol.2021.01.003. Epub 2021 Feb 18. PMID: 33610349.","Macfarlane A, Greenhalgh T. Sodium valproate in pregnancy: what are the risks and should we use a shared decision-making approach? BMC Pregnancy Childbirth. 2018 Jun 1;18(1):200. doi: 10.1186/s12884-018-1842-x. PMID: 29859057; PMCID: PMC5984824.","Harden C, Lu C. Epilepsy in Pregnancy. Neurol Clin. 2019 Feb;37(1):53-62. doi: 10.1016/j.ncl.2018.09.008. PMID: 30470275.","Moore JL, Aggarwal P. Lamotrigine use in pregnancy. Expert Opin Pharmacother. 2012 Jun;13(8):1213-6."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39289"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12344"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18875"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18875"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7f504a8a-3622-4c61-bf63-36d16dfbf9be.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/7f504a8a-3622-4c61-bf63-36d16dfbf9be.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":844}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39289"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-27T10:13:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-19T13:47:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4864"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53829"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{